<p><b>Niklaus Emil Wirth</b> (born <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1934-02-15"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="02-15"><a href="/wiki/February_15" title="February 15">February 15</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1934" title="1934">1934</a></span>) is a <a href="/wiki/Switzerland" title="Switzerland">Swiss</a> <a href="/wiki/Computer_science" title="Computer science">computer scientist</a>, best known for designing several <a href="/wiki/Programming_language" title="Programming language">programming languages</a>, including <a href="/wiki/Pascal_(programming_language)" title="Pascal (programming language)">Pascal</a>, and for pioneering several classic topics in <a href="/wiki/Software_engineering" title="Software engineering">software engineering</a>. In 1984 he won the <a href="/wiki/Turing_Award" title="Turing Award">Turing Award</a> for developing a sequence of innovative computer languages.</p>
